Project Description - Bank Churn Prediction¶

Bank Churn Prediction¶

Objective:¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Context:¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Link to the Kaggle project site:https://www.kaggle.com/barelydedicated/bank-customer-churn-modeling

Data Dictionary:¶

  • RowNumber: Row number.
  • CustomerId: Unique identification key for different customers.
  • Surname: Surname of the customer
  • Credit Score: Credit score is a measure of an individual's ability to pay back the borrowed amount. It is the numerical representation of their creditworthiness. A * credit score is a 3-digit number that falls in the range of 300-900, 900 being the highest.
  • Geography: The country to which the customer belongs.
  • Gender: The gender of the customer.
  • Age: Age of the customer.
  • Tenure: The period of time a customer has been associated with the bank.
  • Balance: The account balance (the amount of money deposited in the bank account) of the customer.
  • NumOfProducts: How many accounts, bank account affiliated products the person has.
  • HasCrCard: Does the customer have a credit card through the bank?
  • IsActiveMember: Subjective, but for the concept
  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary of the customer.
  • Exited: Did they leave the bank after all?

At first glance ...

  • about half of the customers are from France, while the other half is roughly split between Spain and Germany. Let's look more closely at this
  • There are slightly more Female customer, but the gender distribution is mostly uniform
  • No features seem to be experiencing multicolinearity. We will be able to drop one of the Gender columns as keeping both is redundant
  • Balance is normally distributed outside of a large population of balances close to or at zero. Let's look at this further as well.

exit = []
tot = []
ex_rat = []
for c in country:
    ex = df[df[c] == 1]['Exited'].sum()
    to = df[df[c] == 1]['Exited'].count()
    exit.append(ex)
    tot.append(to)
    ex_rat.append(round(ex/to, 2))

Split the Data¶

In [304]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

x_cols = [c for c in list(df.columns) if c != 'Exited']

X = df[x_cols]
y = df['Exited']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=14)

Scale the Data¶

In [305]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X_train)

X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

y_train = np.array(y_train)
y_test = np.array(y_test)

Build the Neural Network¶

In [306]:
from tensorflow.keras import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras import optimizers

model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(12, activation='relu', input_dim=12))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
In [307]:
opt = optimizers.Adam(0.01)

model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
In [308]:
epochs = 10
hist = model.fit(X_train, y_train, batch_size=1000, epochs=epochs, validation_split=0.25)

hist_df = pd.DataFrame(hist.history)

Conclusion¶

In [317]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report as cr

print(cr(y_test, y_pred))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.83      0.97      0.90      1981
           1       0.70      0.25      0.37       519

    accuracy                           0.82      2500
   macro avg       0.77      0.61      0.63      2500
weighted avg       0.80      0.82      0.79      2500
  • After running our model, the precision, recall, and f1-scores look good for predicting customers who will not leave the bank; However, the model does not do as good of a job predicting those who will in fact leave.
  • Looking at the metrics for customers predicted to leave, the recall and f1-score ratios are very low at 0.25 and 0.37 respectively. Precision is okay but not great at 0.69.
  • Based on accuracy, our model does improve across 10 epochs from 0.58 to 0.8
  • Neural networks models are very powerful, but a model can only be as good as the features used to build it. The features we have here were not very highly correlated with customers exiting the bank. This could be one reason why our model returns low predictive scores for recall and f1 when trying to predict customers who will exit the bank.
